02/11/2005
ZAGREB, Croatia -- A new poll finds the majority of Croatians are optimistic about the EU prospects and 51.3 per cent believe the country would be able to enter the Union by 2009.
The survey, conducted by the newspaper Vecernji list, suggests that the EU's recent decision to launch delayed membership talks with Zagreb boosted domestic support for accession.
In other news, the UN war crimes tribunal announced on Tuesday the formal transfer of two cases to Croatian authorities.
Former Croatian Army generals Rahim Ademi and Mirko Norac are charged with crimes against the ethnic Serb population in September 1993.
This is the first case The Hague tribunal has handed to Croatia's judiciary.
(Vecernji list - 02/11/05;
ICTY Web site, HINA - 01/11/05)
